8.  Inner Failure Routes
S = Q₁₄/Δ spans three orders of magnitude across the ETG sample. The blow-up decomposes into two distinct routes, verified by decomposing ln S = ln Q₁₄ − ln Δ relative to the single-channel calibrator baseline:

Route A — Quarter-point inflation (Δ-collapse subdominant):
NGC2859 (S = 0.965, Q₁₄-rise dominated), NGC3945 (S = 2.369, Q₁₄-rise dominated).

Route B — Half-point collapse (Δ-collapse dominant):
NGC3998 (S = 30.63), NGC4203 (S = 10.07). In both cases Δ = 1 − Q₁₂ collapses toward zero while Q₁₄ also rises. NGC4203 specifically: Q₁₄ = 0.621 but more critically Δ = 0.062, giving S = 10.07 through Δ-collapse.

Mixed (both contribute materially):
NGC2974, NGC4278, NGC5582.

Supporting correlations: r(−lnΔ, Q₁₄) = 0.922, r(−lnΔ, Q₃₄) = 0.759, r(−lnΔ, Q₉₀) = 0.678. The inner blow-up is not a late-only overshoot effect; the whole inner profile is pushed upward simultaneously, with the half-point collapse as the most explosive component of the ratio.
9.  Outer Gate Structure
9.1  Exact outer viability boundary
Starting from the exact identity:
u = (X₀ᵤₜ − B₀ᵤₜ) / Rₘₐˣ,   X₀ᵤₜ = V²₀̅ₛ(r₀ᵤₜ) / (Γ₀ r₀ᵤₜ),   B₀ᵤₜ = V̅²ₕₐᵣ(r₀ᵤₜ) / (Γ₀ r₀ᵤₜ)
with B₀ᵤₜ = X₀ᵤₜ(Rₐ + Rₕ), the exact viability boundary u < 1 is:
X₀ᵤₜ < Rₘₐˣ / (1 − Rₐ − Rₕ)
where Rₐ = 0.5 V²ₐᵢₛₖ(r₀ᵤₜ) / V²₀̅ₛ(r₀ᵤₜ) and Rₕ = 0.7 V²ₕᵤₗ(r₀ᵤₜ) / V²₀̅ₛ(r₀ᵤₜ). The disk-only reduction X₀ᵤₜ < Rₘₐˣ/(1 − Rₐ) classifies all 16 ETGs correctly. This is a two-coordinate geometric condition, not a heuristic.
