11.  H+ Branch Mathematics
11.1  Sign gate and suppression structure
For H+ galaxies (Ωᵢⁿ > 1), the rotation law takes the form V²(r) = V̅²ₕₐᵣ(r) + χ₊,₀ᵤₜ(r) + χ₊,ᵢⁿ(r) − χ₋(r). The suppression term is:
χ₋(r) = λʙ ∫₀ʳ e⁻⁻⁻⁻⁻⁻⁻⁻⁻⁻⁻⁻⁻ᴸᐢᴸᵂₛᐟᴸᵂ dV̅²ₕₐᵣ/ds ds
The suppression integral Gₛᵤₚₚ must be computed via the integration-by-parts (IBP) form:
Gₛᵤₚₚ = V̅²ₕₐᵣ(rᵢⁿ) · κ*,   κ* = 1 − (1/xʙ) ∫₀¹ exp(−(1−y)/xʙ) B(y) dy
where B(y) = V̅²ₕₐᵣ(rᵢⁿ y)/V̅²ₕₐᵣ(rᵢⁿ) and xʙ = Lʙ/rᵢⁿ. The exact algebraic decomposition:
κ* = exp(−1/xʙ) + U,   U = (1/xʙ) ∫₀¹ exp(−(1−y)/xʙ)[1 − B(y)] dy
11.2  The J-branch and amplitude cancellation
Defining Δ = 1 − Q₁₂, H(y) = (1 − B(y))/Δ, and substituting xʙ = AΔ:
U = J(A)/A,   J(A) = ∫₀¹ exp(−(1−y)/(AΔ)) H(y) dy
This is exact. The substitution xʙ ∝ Δ is the unique scaling that removes the explicit deficit amplitude from the U prefactor, reducing U to a kernel-weighted integral of the normalised profile shape H(y). This is a structural derivation.
