17.  Conclusion
The MTS framework yields a transport-response law for disk galaxies with cosmological normalisation, photometric scale closure, zero-parameter memory correction, and emergent response branching. LTGs follow a closed first-order law (median RMSE 20.60 km/s, zero free parameters). ETGs form a multi-family, multi-sign response sector with a layered structure.

The ETG sector is governed by a four-condition intersection: profile family, sign gate, inner feasibility (S ≲ 1.70 threshold, 15/16 correct), and outer capacity (u ≤ 1). These are genuinely independent axes, confirmed by cross-correlations ≲ 0.52 between all pairs.

The outer gate factorises exactly into a load coordinate X₀ᵤₜ and a disk-carried cancellation coordinate Rₐ = 0.5V²ₐᵢₛₖ/V²₀̅ₛ. The viability boundary X₀ᵤₜ < Rₘₐˣ/(1 − Rₐ) classifies all 16 ETGs correctly. The gate disk-force term obeys a density-plus-geometry law with stable exponents a ≈ 0.78, b ≈ 1.61 (vs ideal exponential benchmark a = 1, b = 3.4). The softening is a real property of ETG disk kernels, confirmed by direct profile computation.

The inner failure of high-S galaxies decomposes into two routes: Δ-collapse (NGC3998, NGC4203) and Q₁₄-rise (NGC2859, NGC3945), with a mixed class (NGC2974, NGC4278, NGC5582). The two outer routes (low-load NGC2685; disk-buffered NGC3626, NGC3941) are confirmed by pairwise isolation controls. The sign gate and outer gate are structurally distinct sectors, not expressions of the same physical variable.
